00:00:24.870 --> 00:00:26.100
Probability: so what is it?

00:00:26.100 --> 00:00:27.870
And I think all of us
have kind of a sense of

00:00:27.870 --> 00:00:29.560
it, very informally.

00:00:29.560 --> 00:00:32.260
And as far as I can tell there
actually isn't a formal

00:00:32.260 --> 00:00:34.920
definition of what
a probability is.

00:00:34.920 --> 00:00:38.670
There are several almost
formal competing definitions.

00:00:38.670 --> 00:00:41.370
So just in our everyday life,
you know if the weather man

00:00:41.370 --> 00:00:48.810
says there's a 50% percent
chance of rain the next

00:00:48.810 --> 00:00:51.490
day, he's essentially
giving a probability.

00:00:51.490 --> 00:00:54.650
He's saying that-- well,
there's a couple of ways

00:00:54.650 --> 00:00:58.800
that you could interpret
the 50% probability.

00:00:58.800 --> 00:01:04.130
It could be that if 100% was
that he is sure there's rain

00:01:04.130 --> 00:01:08.000
tomorrow and 0% is that he is
not sure that there's is rain

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:10.970
tomorrow, that 50% kind of
means well, he's kind of

00:01:10.970 --> 00:01:12.680
neutral between those
two possibilities.

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:18.330
So one definition could be
how strongly you believe.

00:01:22.240 --> 00:01:25.150
Actually, there's a whole
school of probability where

00:01:25.150 --> 00:01:27.510
they view probability like
this, and it's called the

00:01:27.510 --> 00:01:30.080
Baysian, and we'll
go into that more.

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:32.060
Actually, when we do easy
problems, all of these things

00:01:32.060 --> 00:01:33.330
kind of are the same thing.

00:01:33.330 --> 00:01:37.140
But later on we'll see
what the difference is.

00:01:37.140 --> 00:01:39.390
Another way of interpreting
this and this is kind of the

00:01:39.390 --> 00:01:44.360
frequentist school of thought,
is if I were to have the data

00:01:44.360 --> 00:01:47.200
that this-- or if the weather
man had this data that he has

00:01:47.200 --> 00:01:51.240
right now as far as where the
clouds are and what the

00:01:51.240 --> 00:01:55.910
barometer reads and where the
moon is and all of the data.

00:01:55.910 --> 00:01:59.240
Given all of the data that he
has, when he has that same

00:01:59.240 --> 00:02:05.290
exact data hundred times,
fifty times or 50% of those

00:02:05.290 --> 00:02:07.240
times there will be rain.

00:02:07.240 --> 00:02:11.230
So you can almost view it as,
given the data that he has, if

00:02:11.230 --> 00:02:13.570
you had that data a hundred
times or if you were able to

00:02:13.570 --> 00:02:15.860
run this experiment a hundred
times-- although that's very

00:02:15.860 --> 00:02:19.820
unlikely that you would have
that exact same number

00:02:19.820 --> 00:02:20.760
of data points.

00:02:20.760 --> 00:02:23.200
You know, whether Mars is
in the right place and the

00:02:23.200 --> 00:02:24.610
sun is flaring and all.

00:02:24.610 --> 00:02:27.840
It's very unlikely you have
those exact same-- you know,

00:02:27.840 --> 00:02:28.650
the butterfly effect.

00:02:28.650 --> 00:02:31.500
One butterfly can effect the
wind patterns across the ocean.

00:02:31.500 --> 00:02:35.120
So it's very unlikely that you
could perform that experiment a

00:02:35.120 --> 00:02:38.130
hundred times, but what the
weather man could be saying is

00:02:38.130 --> 00:02:42.430
well, if I did have data
identical to this, a hundred

00:02:42.430 --> 00:02:46.410
times, 50 of those times or
50% of the time we would

00:02:46.410 --> 00:02:48.700
have rain the next day.

00:02:48.700 --> 00:03:01.010
That's 50% of experiments with
same-- I guess you could say

00:03:01.010 --> 00:03:05.650
measurable initial conditions--
I'm kind of doing this on the

00:03:05.650 --> 00:03:07.920
fly so don't take
this as gospel.

00:03:07.920 --> 00:03:09.670
But it I think it'll
give you the sense.

00:03:09.670 --> 00:03:14.700
With same initial conditions,
would result in rain.

00:03:18.120 --> 00:03:22.360
They're almost the same thing,
but we'll see later that this

00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:25.700
frequentist-- I tend to view
the world kind of like this,

00:03:25.700 --> 00:03:27.310
but there are a lot of
circumstances where you

00:03:27.310 --> 00:03:30.940
really-- it's hard to say that
you could perform that same

00:03:30.940 --> 00:03:33.490
exact experiment over again.

00:03:33.490 --> 00:03:37.470
For example, if someone said in
2003 there's a 50% chance or

00:03:37.470 --> 00:03:40.660
there's an 80% chance that
Saddam Hussein has weapons of

00:03:40.660 --> 00:03:43.970
mass destruction, that I think
would-- and that would

00:03:43.970 --> 00:03:44.520
be a probability.

00:03:44.520 --> 00:03:47.770
You know, you'd have these CIA
analysts who aren't being

00:03:47.770 --> 00:03:52.790
influenced by their bosses
saying hey, after all the data

00:03:52.790 --> 00:03:57.590
we see, we can't be sure, but
we think there's an 80% chance.

00:03:57.590 --> 00:03:59.650
They would be in
this camp, right?

00:03:59.650 --> 00:04:01.870
Because you really couldn't
perform that experiment

00:04:01.870 --> 00:04:02.610
a hundred times.

00:04:02.610 --> 00:04:05.870
There haven't been a hundred
times or a thousand times or a

00:04:05.870 --> 00:04:08.430
large number of times where you
had that exact same set of

00:04:08.430 --> 00:04:11.330
circumstances where you a guy
with the big mustache in the

00:04:11.330 --> 00:04:14.710
Middle East kind of giving
the run around for

00:04:14.710 --> 00:04:15.660
weapons inspectors.

